VECTOR SPACE MODEL 


######################################################################################################################
How to set up the search engine ?

1. Unzip Data_Files.zip to your current working directory.

2. The scripts are .ipynb format. So you need juypter IDE to open the python notebooks.

3. Install jupyter notebook and upload the .ipynb files. 

4. Also paste ADM_heapfunctions.py in your current working directory.

5. Execute the file ADM_Query_Processing.ipynb to run the search engine. 
	
	a. Run The last block of code run_query().
	b. Enter your keywords and see the results of the search engine. 


######################################################################################################################
Description of all the files. 

1. ADM_check_non_existing_recipe.ipynb : This checks which of the files scraped do not have any text in it 
					  (since some recipes are taken down from the BBC website, might be 
					   possible that it doesnt exist ) 

2. ADM_clean_data.ipynb : Cleans all the files present in ./ADM_dataset/raw and creates the cleaned files in 
			  ./ADM_dataset/cleaned

3. ADM_Extract_all_links_data.ipynb : Scrapes of all the relevant data from every link present in the file 
				      all_recipe_links.txt

4. ADM_heapfunctions.py : Contains the heap-sort function and other heap functions used to sort the search engine 
			  results ( for faster processing ) 

5. ADM_Inverted_Index.ipynb : Builds the inverted index for the search engine. The file is built with the name 
                              inverted_index.p

6. ADM_Query_Processing.ipynb : This script is for query processing. Maps documents and queries in vector space, 
                                calculates relevant scores between the query and documents, heap sorts the results
                                and displays the ranked results. 
				   
